Step 1: Calculate the Debt to Asset Ratio.
• Total Assets at End_date: 15,653,266.97 
• Total Liabilities: Since the Balance Sheet shows Total Liabilities and Owner's Equity and then the Owner’s Equity (Paid-in Capital + Retained Earnings), the liabilities equal:
  Total Liabilities = Total Liabilities and Owner’s Equity − Total Owner’s Equity 
  = 15,653,266.97 − 14,105,265.77 
  = 1,548,001.20
• Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets 
  = 1,548,001.20 / 15,653,266.97 
  ≈ 0.0989 
Rounded to two decimal places, this ratio is approximately 0.10.

Step 2: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow to Net Income Ratio.
• Operating Net Cash Flow: 803,237.11 (from the cash flow statement)
• Net Income: 1,105,265.77 (from the income statement)
• Operating Cash Flow to Net Income Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / Net Income 
  = 803,237.11 / 1,105,265.77 
  ≈ 0.7270 
Rounded to two decimal places, this ratio is approximately 0.73.

Thus, the answer is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.10",
    "Operating Cash Flow to Net Income Ratio": "0.73"
  }
}
